web_results.snippet: Jellyfish, also known as sea jellies, are the medusa-phase of certain gelatinous members of the subphylum Medusozoa, which is a major part of the phylum Cnidaria. Jellyfish are mainly free-swimming marine animals, although a few are anchored to the seabed by stalks rather than being motile.

related_questions.question: Are jellyfish harmful to humans?
related_questions.snippet: Many types of jellyfish are fairly harmless to humans. Others can cause severe pain and a full-body (systemic) reaction. These jellyfish cause more-serious problems in people: Box jellyfish. Box jellyfish can cause intense pain and, rarely, life-threatening reactions.

related_questions.question: How do you treat a jellyfish sting?
related_questions.snippet: Use water that's 110 to 113 F (43 to 45 C). It should feel hot, not scalding. Keep the affected skin immersed or in a hot shower until the pain eases, which might be 20 to 45 minutes. Apply 0.5% to 1% hydrocortisone cream or ointment twice a day to the affected skin.

buttons.subtitle: Lifespan Of Jellyfish
buttons.title: Jellyfish and Comb Jellies - Smithsonian Ocean
buttons.snippet: Most jellyfish are short lived. Medusa or adult jellyfish typically live for a few months, depending on the species, although some species can live for 2-3 years in captivity. Polyps can live and reproduce asexually for several years, or even decades. One jellyfish species is almost immortal.
snippet_highlighted_words: Medusa or adult jellyfish typically live for a few months, depending on the species, although some species can live for 2-3 years in captivity

buttons.subtitle: What Do Jellyfish Use To Sting
buttons.title: Jellyfish Sting: Symptoms & Treatment - Cleveland Clinic
buttons.snippet: Jellyfish have stinging cells called nematocysts inside of their tentacles. A single tentacle may contain thousands of nematocysts. Nematocysts contain a poisonous substance (venom) that helps jellyfish protect themselves. The venom also helps them capture food by stinging it.
snippet_highlighted_words: stinging cells called nematocysts inside of their tentacles

buttons.subtitle: Jellyfish Life Stages
buttons.title: Jellyfish Lifecycle and Reproduction - Smithsonian Ocean
buttons.snippet: Throughout their lifecycle, jellyfish take on two different body forms: medusa and polyps. Polyps can reproduce asexually by budding, while medusae spawn eggs and sperm to reproduce sexually. Learn more about the lifecycle and reproduction of jellyfish.

buttons.subtitle: Jellyfish Diet
buttons.title: What do jellyfish eat? Understanding the gelatinous sea creature's habits.
buttons.snippet: Jellyfish are carnivores, so their diet mainly consists of other animals. This includes zooplankton, small crustaceans, small fish and other jellyfish, according to Oceana, an ocean conservation nonprofit. Jellyfish will also consume plants, National Geographic reports.
snippet_highlighted_words: zooplankton, small crustaceans, small fish and other jellyfish

buttons.subtitle: Jellyfish Anatomy
buttons.title: Jellies | Animals - Monterey Bay Aquarium
buttons.snippet: Jelly anatomy Jellies are composed of three layers: the epidermis, which is the outer layer; the mesoglea, a middle layer made up of a thick, elastic, jelly-like substance; and the inner layer known as the endoderm gastrodermis.

buttons.subtitle: What Jellyfish Lives Forever
buttons.title: Immortal jellyfish: the secret to cheating death
buttons.snippet: The hydrozoan Turritopsis dohrnii, an animal about 4.5 millimetres wide and tall (likely making it smaller than the nail on your little finger), can actually reverse its life cycle. It has been dubbed the immortal jellyfish.

buttons.subtitle: How To Avoid Jellyfish?
buttons.title: Jellyfish in San Diego: How to Avoid and Treat Stings
buttons.snippet: Consider wearing a wetsuit, which provides a physical barrier against jellyfish stings. Rash guards and other protective clothing can also help reduce the risk of stings.
